<p><FONT size=5 face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" color="#334455"><b><u>Editorials.</u></b></FONT><p><ul><FONT size=3 face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" color="#8b1a1a"><STRONG>What The Dojo meant to me</STRONG></p><ul><p>The weekend that the Dojo went down was an interesting one.  I was away from home unable to play EQ or browse the web; business trips will do that.  After a trip of being worn out and sick, I finally made it home, fired up my PC's, and wanted to catch up on current events in our community.  I wasn't surprised to find the Dojo down at first, it has happened a few times before, and I assumed Jirith was doing a little update or their connection was screwed; again nothing too unusual.  I headed over to ezboard and clicked on my shortcut to the Dojo's forums.  Needless to say when I saw the last post on the Dojo, I was shocked and dismayed.  Like most folks, I read it eagerly hoping to discern some kernel of knowledge about the events that happened while away.  The only new tidbit was the reason why it happened so fast, which is unimportant, and the fact that it was going to happen eventually.</p><p>The Sensei, Chai (his monk on Erollisi Marr), or Rich (to those who took the time to know him) could no longer keep going.  His updates to the site were becoming fewer and farther in between, and we could see something was wrong, but like most things, we couldn't see the forest because of all the trees.  As a web guy myself, I know what its like to be burnt out and not want to update a site.  I thought he was tired and taking a needed and well-deserved rest; wrong answer.  His final post to us, he explained that he just didn't have the heart to keep going; he had all but quit the game and was using the Dojo as a reason to hang on, because he didn't want to disappoint us.  Ironic…  The Sensei, master of the acerbic tongue, wry humor, beating his UTM's when they got out of line, and who was well known to speak his mind, didn't want to tell us he was done.  A tear came to my eye while reading that final post and realized that someone I considered a friend (even though we never truly met and only spoke via e-mail a few times) and a place that I had grown to enjoy and considered in my top five favorite web sites (not just EQ sites either) was gone.  To say I was depressed is an understatement as I perused other sites, reading the rants or tributes to a person that gave monks a home.</p><p>The Dojo was a home for our class, a wealth of information on how to be better at what we do, and it was all wrapped together in a package that said, "Don't be so damn serious about it!!"  I can hardly express what personal value I found within the Dojo, much of the information was old hat for me as I'd already been there and done that, but I recognized the value of the intent and tried to give back to our community.  The best part was that someone actually cared enough to give a piece of themselves, their time, effort, and knowledge, to us without any obvious payout beyond the simple thank you that we all owe to the Sensei and Jirith for providing that home for us.  I, for one, say THANK YOU!!  You have made most of this year bearable as a monk despite the continued nerfs, screw-ups, and role reversal our class has suffered.</p><p>To all of you who have offered concern and tribute to the Dojo and its hosts, THANK YOU for caring!!  I am sure the Sensei appreciates the kind words and I would hope that one day he can look back on his experience with the Dojo and say, "It was worth it."</p><p>Thank you for taking the time to read this.</p><p>Syke Auttic</p><p>Monk lost on Erollisi Marr</p>

